# devkit toolkit conventions

The workspace build/scaffold/release toolkit lives in
`packages/devkit` as the publishable `@dbx-tools/devkit` package. The
`devkit` bin (`bin/devkit.ts`) is a thin commander dispatcher; each
subcommand delegates to a function in `src/` that is also exported
from the package root for programmatic use. Shared plumbing is split
by concern - reach for it before pulling in new deps or rolling your
own:

- `src/shell.ts` - `sh` / `bunx` wrap Bun's `$`. One home for
  command running, output trimming, and exit-code handling.
- `src/git.ts` - `git()` over `sh`.
- `src/package.ts` - `discoverPackages*`, `orderByDependencies`,
  `writeJson`, `toAbsolute` / `toRelative`, `PackageJson` /
  `WorkspacePackage`.
- `src/script.ts` - `runScript`, `fail`, `errorMessage`,
  `nonEmptyLines`.
- `src/agent.ts` - the Mastra script agent (`agentQuery`, `getScriptAgent`).
- `src/project.ts` - `getProject` (the pacwich `FileSystemProject`).
- `src/config.ts` - `getDevkitConfig` (auto-derived scope + repo,
  overridable via a `devkit` key in the consuming repo's root
  `package.json`).

New command modules export a plain async function and are wired into
`bin/devkit.ts`; keep CLI option parsing in the bin, not the module.

## Always await the shell helpers

`sh()`, `bunx()` and `git()` are **async**. Awaiting them is
mandatory: errors only surface (and serial loops only stay serial)
when the promise is awaited.

```ts
// BAD: build failures get swallowed and packages build in parallel.
for (const pkg of packages) {
  bunx(["tsc", "-p", "tsconfig.build.json"], { cwd: pkg.dir });
}

// GOOD
for (const pkg of packages) {
  await bunx(["tsc", "-p", "tsconfig.build.json"], { cwd: pkg.dir });
}
```

## Walk workspaces through `discoverPackages`

Don't re-implement the "scan `workspaces` glob → read each
`package.json`" loop. `discoverPackages(filter?)` is the single
source of truth.

```ts
import { discoverPackages } from "./package.js";

// Default filter: skip private packages.
const all = await discoverPackages();

// Extra criteria: must have a build config.
const buildable = await discoverPackages(
  (pkg) =>
    pkg.meta.private !== true &&
    existsSync(resolve(pkg.dir, "tsconfig.build.json")),
);
```

Use `discoverPackageJsons(includeRoot?)` when you only need paths
(e.g. cleaning every `node_modules`) and want private workspaces in.

## JSON I/O via `writeJson`

`writeJson()` preserves the trailing newline of the original file,
preventing churn against `prettier --write`. Use it instead of
`Bun.write(path, JSON.stringify(value, null, 2))`.

## AI calls via `agentQuery`

`agentQuery(prompt, ctx?, overrides?)` runs the prompt through a
Mastra agent (with `read_files` / git / sandbox tools) and returns
`null` on any failure (no resolvable model, empty response, exhausted
retries). The model comes from the `SCRIPT_MODEL_PROVIDER` env var as
a `provider/model` spec (`databricks/...`, `ollama/...`, or any
Mastra-routed provider). Designed so callers can do
`await agentQuery(...) ?? fallback` without try/catch boilerplate.

## File ops via `Bun.file` / `Bun.write`

These scripts run under `bun`, so prefer `Bun.file(path).text()`
and `Bun.write(path, contents)` over `node:fs`. Use `node:fs`
synchronously only when there's no async equivalent (`rmSync`,
`existsSync`).
